ts first two cases of coronavirus |date=25 February 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=25 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225142623/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/25/coronavirus-live-updates-outbreak-latest-news-italy-italia-deaths-symptoms-china-stocks-wall-street-dow-jones-economy-falls?page=with:block-5e550afd8f086a28115b2205 |archive-date=25 February 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://orf.at/stories/3155602/ |title=Coronavirus: Zwei F\u00e4lle in Tirol best\u00e4tigt |date=25 February 2020 |website=news.ORF.at |language=de |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Busby (now) |first=Mattha |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/25/coronavirus-live-updates-outbreak-latest-news-italy-italia-deaths-symptoms-china-stocks-wall-street-dow-jones-economy-falls?page=with%3Ablock-5e550d8a8f086a28115b222d |title=Coronavirus news: Austria and Croatia report first cases as Tenerife quarantines hotel \u2013 live updates |date=25 February 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=25 February 2020 |last2=Belam |first2=Martin |issn=0261-3077 |last3=Marsh |first3=Sarah |last4=Rourke |first4=Alison |last5=Farrer (earlier) |first5=Martin |last6=Busby |first6=Mattha |last7=Adams |first7=Richard |last8=Parveen |first8=Nazia |last9=Wearden |first9=Graeme}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-25-20-hnk-intl/h_66850dfa7d9602fb4b0d38efdd19d939 |title=Austria's 2 coronavirus cases are Italian citizens |last=Helen Regan |last2=Adam Renton |date=25 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=25 February 2020 |last3=Meg Wagner |last4=Mike Hayes |last5=Veronica Rocha}}</ref> {{As of|2020|04|1|post=,}} Austria has reported 11,171 cases of which 168 have died and 2,022 have recovered.<ref name=\"counter\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sozialministerium.at/Informationen-zum-Coronavirus/Neuartiges-Coronavirus-(2019-nCov).html |title=Informationen zum Coronavirus (2019-nCov)}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n\nOn 25 February 2020, [[Austria]] confirmed the first two cases of [[COVID-19]], a 24-year-old man and a 24-year-old woman from [[Lombardy]], Italy tested positive and were treated at a hospital in [[Innsbruck]], [[Tyrol (state)|Tyrol]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/25/coronavirus-live-updates-outbreak-latest-news-italy-italia-deaths-symptoms-china-stocks-wall-street-dow-jones-economy-falls?page=with:block-5e550afd8f086a28115b2205 |title=Austria reports first two cases of coronavirus |date=25 February 2020 |access-date=25 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225142623/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/25/coronavirus-live-updates-outbreak-latest-news-italy-italia-deaths-symptoms-china-stocks-wall-street-dow-jones-economy-falls?page=with:block-5e550afd8f086a28115b2205 |archive-date=25 February 2020 |work=The Guardian |agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://orf.at/stories/3155602/ |title=Coronavirus: Zwei F\u00e4lle in Tirol best\u00e4tigt |last=red |first=ORF at/Agenturen |date=25 February 2020 |website=news.ORF.at |language=de |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Busby (now) |first=Mattha |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/25/coronavirus-live-updates-outbreak-latest-news-italy-italia-deaths-symptoms-china-stocks-wall-street-dow-jones-economy-falls?page=with%3Ablock-5e550d8a8f086a28115b222d |title=Coronavirus news: Austria and Croatia report first cases as Tenerife quarantines hotel \u2013 live updates |date=25 February 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=25 February 2020 |last2=Belam |first2=Martin  |issn=0261-3077 |last3=Marsh |first3=Sarah |last4=Rourke |first4=Alison |last5=Farrer (earlier) |first5=Martin |last6=Busby |first6=Mattha |last7=Adams |first7=Richard |last8=Parveen |first8=Nazia |last9=Wearden |first9=Graeme}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-25-20-hnk-intl/h_66850dfa7d9602fb4b0d38efdd19d939 |title=Austria's 2 coronavirus cases are Italian citizens |last=Helen Regan |last2=Adam Renton |date=25 February 2020 |publisher=CNN  |access-date=25 February 2020 |last3=Meg Wagner |last4=Mike Hayes |last5=Veronica Rocha}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, a 72-year-old man in [[Vienna]] had been in the Krankenanstalt Rudolfstiftung hospital for 10 days with flu symptoms before he tested positive for [[SARS-CoV-2]]. He was then transferred to Kaiser-Franz-Josef Hospital.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.derstandard.at/jetzt/livebericht/2000115088241/coronaviruserster-bestaetigter-fall-in-wien |title=Dritter best\u00e4tigter Coronavirus-Fall in Wien \u2013 derStandard.at |website=DER STANDARD |language=de-AT |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web |url=https://wien.orf.at/stories/3036506/ |title=Coronavirus: Drei best\u00e4tigte F\u00e4lle in Wien |last=red |first=wien ORF at/Agenturen |date=27 February 2020 |website=wien.ORF.at |language=de |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kurier.at/chronik/wien/coronavirus-erreicht-wien-72-jaehriger-erkrankt/400765893 |title=Coronavirus erreicht Wien: 72-J\u00e4hriger erkrankt |last=birgit.seiser,katharina.zach |website=kurier.at |language=de |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://orf.at/stories/3155857/ |title=Coronavirus: Wiener Patient seit zehn Tagen im Spital |last=red |first=ORF at/Agenturen |date=27 February 2020 |website=news.ORF.at |language=de |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref> A couple who tested positive and their two children who were showing symptoms were admitted to Kaiser-Franz-Josef Hospital. The family had previously been on holiday in Lombardy, Italy.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":13\" /> On 28 February, one of the children, a 15-year-old boy tested positive. Due to the illness, precautions were taken at his high school as 4 teachers and 23 students born between 2003 and 2005 were sent home for isolation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://orf.at/stories/3156035/ |title=Infektion in Steiermark: Bereits sieben best\u00e4tigte CoV-F\u00e4lle |last=red |first=ORF at/Agenturen |date=28 February 2020 |website=news.ORF.at |language=de |access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nBeginning from 1 March, authorities in Germany and the [[Nordic countries]] begun identifying Tyrolean ski resort town of [[Ischgl]] as a major coronavirus hotspot. Several hundred infections were eventually traced back to the town with transmissions having occurred from late February on. After initially playing down the risks, Tyrolean authorities placed the entire town in quarantine on 13 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/the-austrian-ski-town-that-spread-coronavirus-across-the-continent/ |title=The Austrian ski town that spread coronavirus across the Continent |last=Karnitschnig |first=Matthew |date=19 March 2020 |website=Politico |access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2020, the government announced that all universities would close their classes at the latest by 16 March. All outdoor events with more than 500 people and all indoor events with more than 100 people were cancelled. All children older than 14 years old were ordered to stay at home, starting 15 March, with the younger children starting 17 March . This will apply until 4 April.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kleinezeitung.at/politik/5783037/Coronavirus_Stufenweise-ab-Montag_Oesterreich-schliesst-Schulen |title=Coronavirus: Stufenweise ab Montag: \u00d6sterreich schlie\u00dft Schulen \u00ab |date=11 March 2020 |publisher=Kleinezeitung.at |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Travel restrictions for people coming from Italy are established. The government asked the general public to avoid social contact and announced even further restrictions to be made soon.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://orf.at/stories/3157262/ |title=Coronavirus: Starke Einschr\u00e4nkungen beschlossen \u2013 news.ORF.at |last=bock, sita, beide ORF.at/Agenturen |date=10 March 2020 |publisher=Orf.at |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March 2020, Austria confirmed the first death of COVID-19, a 69-year-old man from Vienna died in Vienna's Kaiser-Franz-Josef Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vindobona.org/article/austria-reports-first-death-from-covid-19 |title=Austria Reports First Death from COVID-19 \u2013 Vindobona.org &#124; Vienna International News |publisher=Vindobona.org |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 13 March 2020, there were 422 confirmed cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sozialministerium.at/Informationen-zum-Coronavirus/Neuartiges-Coronavirus-(2019-nCov).html |title=Sozialministerium: Aktuelle Informationen: Neuartiges Coronavirus |language=de |access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPotential COVID-19 infected persons should under no circumstances go to a doctor or to an outpatient clinic to reduce the risk of infection. They were asked to call the [[Healthcare number 1450]] instead. On 15 March, there were about 70 times as many calls as on other Sundays before the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kurier.at/chronik/niederoesterreich/coronavirus-kaum-wartezeit-bei-gesundheitshotline-1450-in-noe/400783847 |title=Coronavirus: Kaum Wartezeit bei Gesundheitshotline 1450 in N\u00d6 |website=kurier.at |language=de |access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, a ban was also announced for public gatherings of more than five people, and restaurants were ordered to close beginning on 17 March.<ref name=\"bloomberg.1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-15/austria-clamps-down-on-public-life-as-coronavirus-cases-soar |title=Austria Coronavirus News: \u00d6sterreich Aktuelle Virus Nachrichten |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=Bloomberg |access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> {{anchor|Lockdown}}In addition, [[G\u00fcnther Platter]], the governor of [[Tyrol (state)|Tyrol]], announced a one-week lockdown for the whole province.<ref name=\"apnews\">{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/16c6a936bd0eecd81d468a993f182890 |title=The Latest: US CDC recommends strict 8-week limit on crowds |date=15 March 2020 |website=AP NEWS}}</ref><ref name=\"boston.globe\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/15/business/austria-shuts-restaurants-bans-some-flights/ |title=Austria's Tyrol province orders lockdown |website=Boston Globe}}</ref> Residents in Tyrol were required to remain in their homes except for necessary reasons such as purchasing food or medicine, visiting the doctor, withdrawing cash, or walking a dog.<ref name=\"apnews\" />\n\nAs of 16 March, nationwide, homes may only be left for one of the following reasons:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://orf.at/stories/3158055/ |title=Ausgangsbeschr\u00e4nkungen \u2013 Was nun erlaubt ist und was nicht \u2013 news.ORF.at |last=ORF.at/Agenturen |date=16 March 2020 |publisher=Orf.at |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n* necessary professional activities\n* necessary purchases (groceries or medication)\n* assisting other people\n* activities outside, alone or in the company of people living in the same household\nOfficials stated that those restrictions are being actively enforced by the police.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 27 March, Federal Minister of Health [[Rudolf Anschober]] announced that, in Austria, the peak of the pandemic is expected to be between mid of April and mid of May 2020.<ref name=\"orf-interview-anschober\">{{Cite news |url=https://orf.at/stories/3159540/ |title=Spitze zwischen 'Mitte April und Mitte Mai' |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020 |website=orf.at}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, the Austrian government announced that everyone entering a store has to wear a [[Surgical mask|face mask]] effective 6 April.<ref name=\"verschaerfung\">{{Cite news |url=https://orf.at/stories/3159909/ |title=Regierung versch\u00e4rft Ma\u00dfnahmen |date=30 March 2020 |access-date=30 March 2020 |agency=ORF |ref=verschaerfung}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Austria medical cases chart}}\n{{As of|2020|4|5|df=}} 3:00 p.m, there were 11,907 total confirmed cases in Austria, 204 of them have officially died, and 2,998 people that have officially recovered. {{As of|2020|4|5|df=}} 09:30&nbsp;am, 108,416 tests have been conducted.<ref name=\"sozialministerium\" />\n\nConfirmed cases, as of 5 April 2020, 8:00 a.m .: 11,767 cases, by federal states: [[Burgenland]] (224), [[Carinthia]] (310), Lower Austria (1,863), Upper Austria (1,916), Salzburg (1,068), Styria (1,285), Tirol (2,690), Vorarlberg (722), Vienna (1,689).\n\nDeaths, as of 3 April 2020, 09:30&nbsp;am: 168, by federal states: Burgenland (3), Carinthia (3), Lower Austria (28), Upper Austria (17), Salzburg (12), Styria (38), Tirol (29), Vorarlberg (4), Vienna (34).<ref name=\"sozialministerium\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sozialministerium.at/Informationen-zum-Coronavirus/Neuartiges-Coronavirus-(2019-nCov).html |title=Aktuelle Informationen: Neuartiges Coronavirus |publisher=[[Federal Ministry of Social Affairs, Health, Care and Consumer Protection]] |language=de |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n<ref group=\"nb\">The numbers published here are the official numbers from the [[Federal Ministry of Social Affairs, Health, Care and Consumer Protection|Sozialministerium]] published daily at 8:00&nbsp;am and 3:00&nbsp;pm. Furthermore, the Federal Ministry of Social Affairs, Health, Care and Consumer Protection, provides frequent updates on http://info.gesundheitsministerium.at</ref>\n\nRecoveries, as of 3 April 2020, 09:30 a.m.:  2,022, by federal states: Burgenland (29), Carinthia (65), Lower Austria (340), Upper Austria (437), Salzburg (136), Styria (103), Tyrol (631), Vorarlberg (183), Vienna (98).\n\n<!-- On 17 March, the death of a fourth person suspected to be infected by COVID-19 was announced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wien.orf.at/stories/3039457/ |title=Vierter Todesfall |date=17 March 2020 |website=ORF}}</ref>. The woman died in home quarantine and was only 48 years old. An [[autopsy]] has been ordered to determine the cause of death. -->\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=800\n|colors=#F46D33\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=No. of new cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y1= 5, 0, 8, 11, 12, 14, 24, 20, 32, 51, 64, 115, 143, 151, 205, 156, 316, 314, 367, 375, 426, 430, 680, 925, 684, 838, 1050, 596, 541, 841, 597, 508, 485, 416, 282, 242\n|y1Title=New cases per day\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n==Prevention measures==\nOn 17 March, in addition to border checks, Austria banned all arrivals from Italy, China's Hubei Province, Iran, and South Korea, excepting those who had a medical certificate no more than four days old that confirmed they were not affected by coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/coronavirus-travel-bans/index.html |title=Coronavirus: Which countries have travel bans? |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020 |publisher=CNN}}</ref> \nOn 27 March, it was announced that no further prevention measures are planned.<ref name=\"orf-interview-anschober\" /> <br />\nOn 30 March, the government laid out plans to introduce compulsory wearing of [[Surgical mask|face masks]] covering mouth and nose. From 6 April onwards, this will only affect persons entering supermarkets, but will be extended to more public places in near future.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://orf.at/stories/3159909/ |title=Regierung versch\u00e4rft Ma\u00dfnahmen |date=30 March 2020 |access-date=30 March 2020 |website=orf.at}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n** {{Cite web |url=https://coronavirus-global.com/austria |title=Coronavirus Austria updates and news |language=English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Finnish, Estonian, Russian |trans-title=Latest news and statistics of coronavirus in Austria. |access-date=4 April 2020}}\n**[https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases] and [https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19 historical data] by [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n**[http://info.gesundheitsministerium.at Interactive map for Austria] by [[Federal Ministry of Social Affairs, Health, Care and Consumer Protection|Sozialministerium]]\n**[https://orf.at/stories/3157517/ Coronavirus: Erster Todesfall in \u00d6sterreich]\n\n{{2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Austria| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Austria]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStatistics:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Austria"}
{"title_page": "David P. B. Fitzpatrick", "text_new": "'''David Patrick Brian Fitzpatrick''' (25 May 1948 \u2013 20 February 2019) was an Irish historian best known for his work on Irish independence and emigration.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/david-fitzpatrick-obituary-the-most-influential-irish-historian-of-his-generation-1.3842878|title=David Fitzpatrick obituary: \u2018The most influential Irish historian of his generation\u2019|website=The Irish Times|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irishhumanities.com/blog/professor-david-patrick-brian-fitzpatrick-sftcd-mria-19482019-a-tribute/|title=Prof. David Fitzpatrick, SFTCD MRIA (1948\u20132019) {{!}} Irish Humanities Alliance|website=irishhumanities.com|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> He was professor of Modern History at [[Trinity College Dublin]] and a member of the [[Royal Irish Academy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ria.ie/publications/author/david-fitzpatrick|title=David Fitzpatrick|website=Royal Irish Academy|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://president.ie/index.php/en/media-library/news-releases/statement-by-president-higgins-on-the-death-of-prof-david-fitzpatrick|title=Media Library News Releases|last=Ireland|first=Office of the President of|website=president.ie|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref>\n\n[[R.F. Foster (historian)|Roy Foster]] referred to him as \u201cthe most original and influential Irish historian of his generation\u201d and [[Diarmuid Ferriter]] considers him \"one of the most brilliant historians of his generation\". [[Cormac O Grada]] has stated he \"will be remembered for his deep, sometimes contrarian, insights and for his takes on a bewilderingly wide range of themes\u201d.<ref name=:0/><ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/independence-narrative-must-be-freed-of-sweeping-statements-1.3803020</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nFitzpatrick was born in Melbourne, Australia to [[Brian Fitzpatrick (Australian author)|Brian Charles Fitzpatrick]], an author and journalist and mother Dorothy Mary (n\u00e9e Davies) a historian at the Monash University.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/version/24757488|title=Papers of Dorothy Fitzpatrick, 1929-2003|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Dorothy|last2=Douglas|first2=-2009, Alan|date=1929|language=English}}</ref> His elder sister, [[Sheila Fitzpatrick]] is a historian of modern Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0468b.htm|title=Fitzpatrick, Sheila Mary - Woman - The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in Twentieth-Century Australia|last=Melbourne|first=The University of|website=www.womenaustralia.info|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> At birth, Fitzpatrick was given three names as their parents could not decide on either David, Brian or Patrick. To the family he was initially known as Pat, but later took to using his first name.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cEruMXjqme0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=My+Father%E2%80%99s+Daughter:+Memories+of+an+Australian+Childhood&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ptOvorLhAhWhoXEKHXXbByIQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage|title=My Father's Daughter: Memories of an Australian Childhood|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Sheila|date=|publisher=Melbourne Univ. Publishing|year=2010|isbn=9780522857474|location=|pages=58, 138}}</ref>\n\nHis parents instilled in their children a strong sense of academic achievement. Two months before his Matriculation examinations his father died during a research trip to Sydney.<ref>{{Cite book Don Watson, Brian Fitzpatrick: A Radical Life, Hale & Iremonger, 1979, p. 287}}</ref> His parents were not separated as claimed elsewhere. Fitzpatrick nevertheless topped the State of Victoria in Modern History, adding an Exhibition to his other awards and scholarships. He went on to study history at the University of Melbourne and resided at Trinity College.<ref name=\":1\" /> His first foray into Irish history, through his love of the poetry of W.B. Yeats, was his B.A. Hons.thesis, 'The Dancer and the Dance: The Social and Political Ideas and Activities of William Butler Yeats from 1916 to 1928'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.history.esrc.unimelb.edu.au/theses/bib/P000600.htm|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>  Fitzpatrick graduated in 1969 before moving to [[La Trobe University]] as a tutor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/people/david-fitzpatrick-1948-2019|title=David Fitzpatrick, 1948-2019|last=Reisz|first=Matthew|date=2019-04-04|website=Times Higher Education (THE)|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> After discussions there with the fellow Irish historian John O'Brien, he moved to do a PhD at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"ae-info.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ae-info.org/ae/Member/Fitzpatrick_David|title=Academy of Europe: Fitzpatrick David|website=www.ae-info.org|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Academic career ==\nFitzpatrick spent his professional life at Trinity College Dublin, where he was appointed a lecturer in Modern History in 1979.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1982 he was made a [[Fellow]], an [[Associate professor|Associate Professor]] 1993 and a [[Professor]] in 2000.<ref name=\"ae-info.org\"/> Prior his move to Dublin, he spent time as a Prize Research Fellow between 1975 and 1977 at [[Nuffield College, Oxford]] and returned to the University of Melbourne for two years as a research fellow (1977\u201379). He published his first book, ''Politics and Irish Life, 1913-1921: Provincial Experience of War and Revolution'' in 1977. Based on his PhD thesis the publication was described as 'fair, balanced and neutral, with a touch of irreverence, indeed a model of objectivity'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/twoirelands1912100fitz|title=Politics and Irish Life, 1913-1921: Provincial Experience of War and Revolution, David Fitzpatrick. (Cork University Press, \u00a314.95) ISBN 1859181740 The Two Irelands, 1912-1939, David Fitzpatrick. (Oxford University Press, \u00a38.95)|isbn=0-19-289240-1|last=Mitchell|first=Arthur|date=2013-02-06|website=History Ireland|access-date=2019-04-05|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nFitzpatrick was married twice.<ref name=\":0\" /> He first married Georgina Huege de Serville (known as Haigh) a historian who studied the Australian War Trails.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/australias-war-crimes-trials-1945-51-georgina-fitzpatrick-tim-mccormack-and-narrelle-morris|title=Australia\u2019s War Crimes Trials 1945-51 by Georgina Fitzpatrick, Tim McCormack and Narrelle Morris|last=|first=|date=2017-05-16|website=State Library of NSW|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> They had a son, Brian and daughter, Margaret. The marriage was dissolved in 1999. His second marriage was to Jane Leonard, an Irish military historian, with whom he had two daughters, Julia and Hannah. He died, aged 70 in Belfast after suffering a long illness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://notices.irishtimes.com/death/fitzpatrick-david/54874096|title=FITZPATRICK, DAVID : Death notice - Irish Times Family Notices|website=notices.irishtimes.com|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tributes.theage.com.au/obituaries/theage-au/obituary.aspx?n=david-patrick-brian-fitzpatrick&pid=191626381|title=David Patrick Brian Fitzpatrick|last=|first=|date=23 February 2019|website=theage.com.au|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n==== Monographs ====\n''Politics and Irish Life, 1913-1921: Provincial Experience of War and Revolution'' (Gill & MacMillan, 1977)\n\n''Irish Emigration 1801-1921'' (Economic and Social History Society of Ireland, 1984)\n\n''Oceans of Consolation: Personal Accounts of Irish Migration to Australia'' (Cornell University Press, 1994)\n\n''The Two Irelands: 1912-1939'' (Oxford University Press, 1998)\n\n''Harry Boland's Irish Revolution, 1887-1922'' (Cork University Press, 2004)\n\n''Solitary and Wild: Frederick MacNeice and the Salvation of Ireland'' (Lilliput Press, 2012)\n\n''Descendancy: Irish Protestant Histories since 1795'' (Cambridge University Press, 2017)\n\n''Ernest Blythe in Ulster: The Making of a Double Agent?'' (Cork University Press, 2018)\n\n''The Americanisation of Ireland: Migration and Settlement, 1841-1925'' (Cambridge University Press, 2019)\n\n==== Edited volumes ====\n''Ireland and the First World War'' (Trinity History Workshop, 1986)\n\n''Revolution?: Ireland 1917-1923'' (Trinity History Workshop, 1990)\n\n''Henry Stratford Persse's Letters from Galway to America, 1821-1832'' (Irish Narrative Series) (Cork University Press, 1998)\n\n''Terror in Ireland 1916-1923'' (Trinity History Workshop, 2012)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitzpatrick, David P. B.}}\n[[Category:Irish historians]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''David Patrick Brian Fitzpatrick''' (25 May 1948 \u2013 20 February 2019) was an Irish historian best known for his work on Irish independence and emigration.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/david-fitzpatrick-obituary-the-most-influential-irish-historian-of-his-generation-1.3842878|title=David Fitzpatrick obituary: \u2018The most influential Irish historian of his generation\u2019|website=The Irish Times|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irishhumanities.com/blog/professor-david-patrick-brian-fitzpatrick-sftcd-mria-19482019-a-tribute/|title=Prof. David Fitzpatrick, SFTCD MRIA (1948\u20132019) {{!}} Irish Humanities Alliance|website=irishhumanities.com|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> He was professor of Modern History at [[Trinity College Dublin]] and a member of the [[Royal Irish Academy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ria.ie/publications/author/david-fitzpatrick|title=David Fitzpatrick|website=Royal Irish Academy|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://president.ie/index.php/en/media-library/news-releases/statement-by-president-higgins-on-the-death-of-prof-david-fitzpatrick|title=Media Library News Releases|last=Ireland|first=Office of the President of|website=president.ie|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref>\n\n[[R.F. Foster (historian)|Roy Foster]] referred to him as \u201cthe most original and influential Irish historian of his generation\u201d and [[Diarmuid Ferriter]] considers him \"one of the most brilliant historians of his generation\". [[Cormac O Grada]] has stated he \"will be remembered for his deep, sometimes contrarian, insights and for his takes on a bewilderingly wide range of themes\u201d.<ref name=:0/><ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/independence-narrative-must-be-freed-of-sweeping-statements-1.3803020</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nFitzpatrick was born in Melbourne, Australia to [[Brian Fitzpatrick (Australian author)|Brian Charles Fitzpatrick]], an author and journalist and mother Dorothy Mary (n\u00e9e Davies) a historian at the Monash University.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/version/24757488|title=Papers of Dorothy Fitzpatrick, 1929-2003|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Dorothy|last2=Douglas|first2=-2009, Alan|date=1929|language=English}}</ref> His elder sister, [[Sheila Fitzpatrick]] is a historian of modern Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0468b.htm|title=Fitzpatrick, Sheila Mary - Woman - The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in Twentieth-Century Australia|last=Melbourne|first=The University of|website=www.womenaustralia.info|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> At birth, Fitzpatrick was given three names as their parents could not decide on either David, Brian or Patrick. To the family he was initially known as Pat, but later took to using his first name.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cEruMXjqme0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=My+Father%E2%80%99s+Daughter:+Memories+of+an+Australian+Childhood&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ptOvorLhAhWhoXEKHXXbByIQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage|title=My Father's Daughter: Memories of an Australian Childhood|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Sheila|date=|publisher=Melbourne Univ. Publishing|year=2010|isbn=9780522857474|location=|pages=58, 138}}</ref>\n\nHis parents instilled in their children a strong sense of academic achievement. Two months before his Matriculation examinations his father died during a research trip to Sydney.<ref>{{Cite book Don Watson, Brian Fitzpatrick: A Radical Life, Hale & Iremonger, 1979, p. 287}}</ref> His parents were not separated as claimed elsewhere. Fitzpatrick nevertheless topped the State of Victoria in Modern History, adding an Exhibition to his other awards and scholarships. He went on to study history at the University of Melbourne and resided at Trinity College.<ref name=\":1\" /> His first foray into Irish history, through his love of the poetry of W.B. Yeats, was his B.A. Hons.thesis, 'The Dancer and the Dance: The Social and Political Ideas and Activities of William Butler Yeats from 1916 to 1928'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.history.esrc.unimelb.edu.au/theses/bib/P000600.htm|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>  Fitzpatrick graduated in 1969 before moving to [[La Trobe University]] as a tutor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/people/david-fitzpatrick-1948-2019|title=David Fitzpatrick, 1948-2019|last=Reisz|first=Matthew|date=2019-04-04|website=Times Higher Education (THE)|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> After discussions there with the fellow Irish historian John O'Brien, he moved to do a PhD at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"ae-info.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ae-info.org/ae/Member/Fitzpatrick_David|title=Academy of Europe: Fitzpatrick David|website=www.ae-info.org|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Academic career ==\nFitzpatrick spent his professional life at Trinity College Dublin, where he was appointed a lecturer in Modern History in 1979.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1982 he was made a [[Fellow]], an [[Associate professor|Associate Professor]] 1993 and a [[Professor]] in 2000.<ref name=\"ae-info.org\"/> Prior his move to Dublin, he spent time as a Prize Research Fellow between 1975 and 1977 at [[Nuffield College, Oxford]] and returned to the University of Melbourne for two years as a research fellow (1977\u201379). He published his first book, ''Politics and Irish Life, 1913-1921: Provincial Experience of War and Revolution'' in 1977. Based on his PhD thesis the publication was described as 'fair, balanced and neutral, with a touch of irreverence, indeed a model of objectivity'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/twoirelands1912100fitz|title=Politics and Irish Life, 1913-1921: Provincial Experience of War and Revolution, David Fitzpatrick. (Cork University Press, \u00a314.95) ISBN 1859181740 The Two Irelands, 1912-1939, David Fitzpatrick. (Oxford University Press, \u00a38.95)|isbn=0-19-289240-1|last=Mitchell|first=Arthur|date=2013-02-06|website=History Ireland|access-date=2019-04-05|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nFitzpatrick was married twice.<ref name=\":0\" /> He first married Georgina Huege de Serville (known as Haigh) a historian who studied the Australian War Trails.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/australias-war-crimes-trials-1945-51-georgina-fitzpatrick-tim-mccormack-and-narrelle-morris|title=Australia\u2019s War Crimes Trials 1945-51 by Georgina Fitzpatrick, Tim McCormack and Narrelle Morris|last=|first=|date=2017-05-16|website=State Library of NSW|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> They had a son, Brian and daughter, Margaret. The marriage was dissolved in 1999. His second marriage was to Jane Leonard, an Irish military historian, with whom he had two daughters, Julia and Hannah. He died, aged 70 in Belfast after suffering a long illness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://notices.irishtimes.com/death/fitzpatrick-david/54874096|title=FITZPATRICK, DAVID : Death notice - Irish Times Family Notices|website=notices.irishtimes.com|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tributes.theage.com.au/obituaries/theage-au/obituary.aspx?n=david-patrick-brian-fitzpatrick&pid=191626381|title=David Patrick Brian Fitzpatrick|last=|first=|date=23 February 2019|website=theage.com.au|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n==== Monographs ====\n''Politics and Irish Life, 1913-1921: Provincial Experience of War and Revolution'' (Gill & MacMillan, 1977)\n\n''Irish Emigration 1801-1921'' (Economic and Social History Society of Ireland, 1984)\n\n''Oceans of Consolation: Personal Accounts of Irish Migration to Australia'' (Cornell University Press, 1994)\n\n''The Two Irelands: 1912-1939'' (Oxford University Press, 1998)\n\n''Harry Boland's Irish Revolution, 1887-1922'' (Cork University Press, 2004)\n\n''Solitary and Wild: Frederick MacNeice and the Salvation of Ireland'' (Lilliput Press, 2012)\n\n''Descendancy: Irish Protestant Histories since 1795'' (Cambridge University Press, 2017)\n\n''Ernest Blythe in Ulster: The Making of a Double Agent?'' (Cork University Press, 2018)\n\n''The Americanisation of Ireland: Migration and Settlement, 1841-1925'' (Cambridge University Press, 2019)\n\n==== Edited volumes ====\n''Ireland and the First World War'' (Trinity History Workshop, 1986)\n\n''Revolution?: Ireland 1917-1923'' (Trinity History Workshop, 1990)\n\n''Henry Stratford Persse's Letters from Galway to America, 1821-1832'' (Irish Narrative Series) (Cork University Press, 1998)\n\n''Terror in Ireland 1916-1923'' (Trinity History Workshop, 2012)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitzpatrick, David P. B.}}\n[[Category:Irish historians]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_P._B._Fitzpatrick"}
